        <listObject>
            <object type="novel">
                <objectIdentifier xml:id="Colsdream">
                    <msName>The Colonel's Dream</msName>
                </objectIdentifier>
                <note><hi rend="italic">The Colonel's Dream</hi> (1905) was Chesnutt's final novel.
                    The book gained little critical attention and didn't sell well&#8212;a reality
                    that stood in opposition to the book's dedication: "to bring the forces of
                    enlightenment to bear upon the vexed problems which harass the South." <hi
                    rend="italic">The Colonel's Dream</hi> tells the story of Colonel French, a
                    successful New York businessman and recent widow who returns to his Southern
                    birthplace, Clarendon, with his son, Phil. French attempts to advance
                    Clarendon's social and economic progress for the modern era, hoping to overcome
                    its prejudices, rigid social divisions, and corruptions and finds a nemesis in
                    the wealthy convict labor contractor, William Fetters. Ultimately, French
                    underestimates the entrenched racism of the town, and despite his best efforts,
                    Clarendon appears wholly unchanged.</note>
            </object>
        </listObject>
